'''Leslie P. Hume''' is an American historian and philanthropist from [[San Francisco, California]]. She has published scholarship about the place of women in the Victorian era as well as women's suffrage societies. She served as President of the Board of Trustees of [[Stanford University]] from 2008 to 2012, making her the second woman after [[Jane Stanford]] ever to do so.

==Biography==
===Early life===
Leslie Parker Hume graduated from [[Radcliffe College]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] in 1989, where she received a Bachelor of Arts degree in History.<ref name="stanfordreport">[http://news.stanford.edu/news/2008/april16/glancebox-041608.html At a glance: Incoming Board of Trustees Chair Leslie P. Hume] Stanford Report, April 16, 2008</ref> She received a Master's degree in 1971 and a PhD in 1979 from [[Stanford University]] in [[Stanford, California]].<ref name="stanfordreport"/><ref name="stanfordpacs">[http://pacscenter.stanford.edu/overview/board/leslie-hume Stanford PACS: Center on Philanthropy and Society: Leslie Hume]</ref>

===Scholarly career===
She edited a volume about women during the Victorian era in 1981 and wrote a book about women's suffrage societies from 1897 to 1914 in 1982.<ref name="stanfordreport"/> She also worked as a consultant for the [[Research Libraries Group]] in [[Mountain View, California]].<ref name="stanfordreport2000">[http://news.stanford.edu/news/2000/december13/hume-1213.html Leslie Hume elected to Board of Trustees], Stanford Report, December 13, 2000</ref>

===Philanthropy===
She has served on the Boards of Trustees of [[The San Francisco Foundation]], the [[San Francisco Opera]], [[Breakthrough Collaborative|Summerbridge National]], and the [[Bay Area Discovery Museum]].<ref name="bloomberg">[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=3803746&privcapId=246618&previousCapId=3571487&previousTitle=Prologis%20LP Leslie P. Hume], ''[[Bloomberg BusinessWeek]]''</ref> She was a founding member of the Board of Trustees of the [[San Francisco Day School]], where she served as its President.<ref name="bloomberg"/>

She was elected to the Board of Trustees of Stanford University in 2000.<ref name="stanfordreport2000"/> She served as its President from 2008 to 2012, making her the second woman after [[Jane Stanford]] to do so.<ref name="stanfordpacs"/><ref>Kathleen J. Sullivan, [http://news.stanford.edu/pr/2008/pr-chair-041608.html Board of Trustees elects Leslie Parker Hume new board president], Stanford News Service, April 16, 2008</ref><ref>Kathleen J. Sullivan, [http://news.stanford.edu/news/2012/february/denning-chair-trustees-021412.html Steven A. Denning elected chair of Stanford University Board of Trustees], Stanford Report, February 14, 2012</ref> She serves co-Chair the 2013-2014 Advisory Council of Stanford Live, the perfoming arts organization at Stanford.<ref>[https://live.stanford.edu/about Stanford Live]</ref> With her husband, she endowed some fellowships for undergraduate students at Stanford University.<ref>[http://shc.stanford.edu/fellowships/stanford-undergraduates Stanford University: Fellowships: Stanford Undergraduates]</ref> They also endowed the ''Hume Center for Writing and Speaking'' at Stanford University.<ref>[https://undergrad.stanford.edu/tutoring-support/hume-center/about-hume-center/mission-and-history Hume Center for Writing and Speaking]</ref>

===Personal life===
She is married to [[George H. Hume]], a businessman, philanthropist, and heir to the [[Basic American Foods]] fortune.<ref name="stanfordreport"/><ref name="stanfordpacs"/> They had a son, Parker Hume, and a daughter, Lilah Hume.<ref name="stanfordreport"/><ref name="stanfordpacs"/>

==Bibliography==
===An an editor===
*''Victorian Women: A Documentary Account of Women's Lives in 19th-Century England, France and the United States'' (Stanford, California: Stanford University Press, 1981).<ref name="stanfordreport"/>
===As an author===
*''The National Union of Women's Suffrage Societies, 1897-1914'' (Garland Publishing, 1982).<ref>[http://books.google.com.au/books/about/The_National_Union_of_Women_s_Suffrage_S.html?id=pJmIAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y Google Books]</ref>

